  1. Use rename() to rename the columns and make them easier to use. The new column names should be:
  • country
  • commname
  • ASFIS_sciname
  • ASFIS_spcode
  • ISSCAAP_spgroup
  • ISSCAAP_spgroupname
  • FAO_area
  • unit
fisheries <- 
  fisheries %>% 
  dplyr::rename(country = Country,
                commname = `Common name`,
                ISSCAAP_spgroup = `ISSCAAP group#`,
                ASFIS_spcode =`ASFIS species#`,
                ASFIS_sciname = `ASFIS species name`,
               ISSCAAP_spgroupname = `ISSCAAP taxonomic group`,
               FAO_area = `FAO major fishing area`,
               unit = Measure)

  1. Are these data tidy? Why or why not, and, how do you know? Use the appropriate pivot function to tidy the data. Remove the NAs. Put the tidy data frame into a new object fisheries_tidy. The data is not tidy because all of the year columns are data and should be pivotted longer.
fisheries_tidy <- 
  fisheries %>% 
  pivot_longer(`1950`:`2012`,
               names_to = "year",
               values_to = "catch")

  1. Use the data to do at least one exploratory analysis of your choice. What can you learn? I want to know which country caught the most octopus in 1963. The answer is Italy
fisheries_tidy %>% 
  filter(str_detect(commname, "octopus")) %>% 
  filter(year == 1963) %>% 
  group_by(country) %>% 
  summarise(catch = sum(catch, na.rm = T)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(catch))
